# Project Context
This is an AI engineering project. The developer is learning through hands-on building,
so explanations should be included alongside code when introducing new patterns.

# Developer Profile
- Background: QA engineering (strong on testing, edge cases, validation logic)
- Learning focus: AI/ML engineering, Python, mobile app development
- Stack: Python, Expo/React Native, Anthropic Claude API
- Goal: Build portfolio-ready, production-quality projects — not just demos

# General Principles
- Prefer clarity over cleverness. Code should be readable and well-commented.
- Always explain WHY a pattern is used, not just WHAT it does.
- Suggest edge cases and input validation — leverage the QA mindset.
- When multiple approaches exist, briefly list the tradeoffs before picking one.
- Prefer modular, reusable code. Build components/functions that can be repurposed across projects.

# Python Rules
- Use Python 3.10+
- Follow PEP 8 style conventions
- Use type hints on all function signatures
- Use docstrings on all functions and classes
- Prefer dataclasses or Pydantic models over raw dicts for structured data
- Use pathlib over os.path
- Handle exceptions explicitly — never bare `except:`
- Use virtual environments (venv); assume one is active
- For AI/ML work: prefer LangChain or direct Anthropic SDK depending on complexity

# AI / LLM Rules
- Use the official Anthropic Python SDK (`anthropic`) for Claude API calls
- Always define system prompts as separate string constants, not inline
- Structure prompts clearly: system role, context, task, output format
- Add retry logic for API calls (network failures happen)
- Never hardcode API keys — use `.env` files and `python-dotenv`
- Log token usage when possible for cost awareness
- When building RAG or retrieval: chunk thoughtfully, don't just split by character count

# Testing Rules (lean into QA background)
- Write tests alongside features, not after
- Use pytest as the testing framework
- Aim for: happy path + at least 2 edge cases per function
- For AI outputs: test that responses are non-empty and match expected structure
- Mock external API calls in tests (don't hit real APIs in test suite)

# React Native / Expo Rules
- Use Expo managed workflow unless ejecting is explicitly required
- Use TypeScript (`.tsx`) for all components
- Follow component structure: imports → types → component → styles
- Use `StyleSheet.create()` for styles, not inline style objects
- Keep components small and single-responsibility
- Use React Navigation for routing
- Handle loading and error states explicitly in every screen
- Consider Arabic RTL layout support: use `I18nManager` where relevant

# File & Folder Structure
- Group by feature, not by file type
  Good:  /features/chat/ChatScreen.tsx, chat.service.ts, chat.types.ts
  Bad:   /screens/ChatScreen.tsx, /services/chat.ts, /types/chat.ts
- Keep reusable utilities in /utils or /lib
- Keep all prompt templates in /prompts folder
- Environment config in .env (never committed to git)

# What to Avoid
- Don't use deprecated libraries or APIs
- Don't generate placeholder "TODO" code — write the real implementation
- Don't skip error handling to keep examples short
- Don't use `any` type in TypeScript unless absolutely necessary
- Don't suggest no-code solutions — hands-on coding is the priority here
